            <fr:title text="Intersections (and unions)">Intersections (and unions)</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>There are a couple of operations on sets that are useful to know about, called <html:strong>intersection</html:strong> and <html:strong>union</html:strong>.
These are not super-central to this unit, but they will come up now and again.
(Intersection will turn out to be more useful for our purposes than union.)</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>17</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/002P/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>002P</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/002P/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Intersection and union">Intersection and union</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Given sets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex>, their <html:strong>intersection</html:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \cap  \Delta ]]></fr:tex> is the set whose members are exactly the things that are members of <html:em>both</html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex>.
Their <html:strong>union</html:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \cup  \Delta ]]></fr:tex> is the set whose members are exactly the things that are members of <html:em>either</html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ]]></fr:tex>.
(Remember <fr:link href="/lectures/000E/" title="Logicians' Weird Habit 1" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/000E/" display-uri="000E" type="local">logicians' weird habit 1</fr:link> here!)</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>For example, the intersection of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p, q, r\}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{q, r, s\}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{q, r\}]]></fr:tex>; and the union of these same two sets is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p, q, r, s\}]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>Intersections and unions don't need to be between exactly two sets: you can take the intersection of a whole bunch of sets, and it contains whatever they <html:em>all</html:em> have in common; and you can likewise take the union of a whole bunch of sets, and it contains whatever is contained in <html:em>any</html:em> of them.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
